        <p><strong>Note on pricing:</strong> Annual billing reduces costs by approximately 20%. For a team of 10 on the Business plan, that's $290/mo on annual vs. $348/mo monthly. Free plan is genuinely useful for evaluation or small projects — not just a crippled demo version.</p>

        <h2>Core features</h2>

        <h3>Plan management</h3>
        <p>This is Fieldwire's foundational feature and its strongest. Upload PDF drawings and they're instantly available on every device — iPad, Android tablet, phone, desktop. Team members can view, mark up, and annotate plans with text, shapes, photos, and hyperlinks between sheets. Version control ensures everyone is always looking at the current set.</p>

        <p>The plan overlay feature lets you compare two revisions side-by-side or overlaid, which is genuinely useful for identifying what changed between drawing sets.</p>

        <h3>Task management</h3>
        <p>Fieldwire's tasks are connected to specific plan locations — you can "pin" a task to a room or area on the drawing. This makes field communication far more precise than "the issue is in the northeast corner" — you see exactly where on the plan. Tasks include status tracking, assignees, due dates, priority levels, and photo attachments.</p>

        <p>For punch list management, this location-linked task system is particularly powerful. Each punch item is tagged to the plan, assigned to the responsible trade, and tracked to completion.</p>

        <h3>Forms and inspections</h3>
        <p>Custom forms are available on Business and higher plans. Safety checklists, daily inspection forms, quality control checklists — these can be built in Fieldwire and completed on mobile. Completed forms are stored against the project and can be exported as PDFs for documentation.</p>

        <h3>Offline functionality</h3>
        <p>This deserves specific mention because it's genuinely useful on job sites: Fieldwire works offline. Plans, tasks, and forms are cached on the device and sync automatically when connectivity is restored. In basements, remote sites, and buildings under construction with spotty service, this is a practical advantage over cloud-only tools.</p>

        <h3>BIM support</h3>
        <p>Business plan and above includes BIM model viewing. 3D models can be imported and navigated, with the ability to create tasks linked to model elements. This puts Fieldwire into the same conversation as Procore's field tools for BIM-enabled commercial projects.</p>

        <h3>Reporting and analytics</h3>
        <p>Pro and above includes project reporting: task completion rates, overdue items by trade, form submission history. Business Plus adds advanced analytics dashboards. For a superintendent managing a large commercial job, these reports provide real-time visibility into where the job is running behind.</p>

        <h2>What Fieldwire does exceptionally well</h2>

        <h3>Ease of use in the field</h3>
        <p>The mobile interface was clearly designed by people who actually visited job sites. Large tap targets, readable fonts, fast loading. Field workers who resist technology tend to accept Fieldwire more readily than office-first platforms. This matters for adoption.</p>

        <h3>Plan distribution and version control</h3>
        <p>On projects where drawing sets update frequently, Fieldwire's version control prevents the nightmare scenario of a crew working from old plans. Upload a revision, mark it current, and everyone immediately has the new set. This single capability has prevented expensive rework on countless projects.</p>

        <h3>Punch list management</h3>
        <p>Fieldwire is the best punch list tool in the market for its price point. The combination of location-pinned tasks, photo documentation, and trade assignment makes the final punch-out process significantly faster than clipboard + email.</p>

        <h3>Free plan value</h3>
        <p>The free plan includes 3 projects with core functionality. For a small contractor evaluating the platform or for a single critical project, this is genuine value — not a free trial that cripples features to force an upgrade.</p>

        <h2>Where Fieldwire falls short</h2>

        <h3>No financial tools</h3>
        <p>This is the critical limitation and must be stated clearly: Fieldwire has no budget management, no change orders, no invoicing, and no client billing. It is purely a field coordination tool. If you're a GC managing job finances, you'll need a separate platform (Buildertrend, JobTread, Procore) for the financial side.</p>

        <h3>Per-user pricing adds up</h3>
        <p>At $29/user/mo, a crew of 20 field workers costs $580/mo just for Fieldwire — and that's the Business tier, which is mid-level. Companies evaluating Fieldwire for large teams should model this cost carefully. Platforms like Buildertrend with unlimited users may end up cheaper for larger operations even at higher base prices.</p>

        <h3>Not a scheduling tool</h3>
        <p>Fieldwire manages tasks but doesn't do scheduling in the Gantt sense. There's no dependency tracking, no critical path, and no project timeline view. Tasks have due dates, but this is not construction scheduling. You'll need a separate tool for project scheduling.</p>

        <h3>Less useful for residential construction</h3>
        <p>Fieldwire's strengths shine most on commercial projects with multiple trades, complex drawing sets, and formal punch processes. For residential remodeling or custom homes, full-platform tools like Buildertrend or JobTread typically provide more value because they combine field and financial management.</p>

        <h2>Who should use Fieldwire</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Superintendents</strong> on commercial projects managing multiple trades</li>
          <li><strong>Subcontractors</strong> who need plan access without paying for a full PM platform</li>
          <li><strong>GCs already using Procore or Buildertrend</strong> for finances who want a best-in-class field layer</li>
          <li><strong>Specialty contractors</strong> (MEP, framing, concrete) who need task coordination on complex jobs</li>
          <li><strong>Small teams</strong> on the free plan for basic plan sharing and punch lists</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Who should look elsewhere</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>Contractors who need budgeting, invoicing, or change orders → Buildertrend or JobTread</li>
          <li>Residential remodelers managing homeowner clients → Buildertrend or Houzz Pro</li>
          <li>Solo contractors or very small teams → Fieldwire's per-user pricing isn't cost-effective</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Fieldwire vs. Procore Field Tools</h2>
        <p>For commercial field management, the real comparison is Fieldwire vs. Procore's field tools module. Procore is deeper and integrates with its full suite; Fieldwire is more accessible and better for companies that don't want to buy Procore's entire platform. If you're on Procore already, use its field tools. If you're not, Fieldwire is the best standalone field management option.</p>

